WEBVTT

00:04.070 --> 00:06.834
The Christmas tree seems
to inspire a love-hate relationship.

00:07.007 --> 00:10.204
All that time is spent
selecting it and decorating it...

00:10.377 --> 00:13.210
...and then a week after,
it's just thrown somewhere.

00:13.380 --> 00:16.406
You see it by the side of the road.
It looks like a mob hit.

00:16.583 --> 00:20.781
The car slows down, the door opens,
and this tree just rolls out.

00:22.522 --> 00:26.049
People snap out of that Christmas
spirit like it was a drunken stupor.

00:26.226 --> 00:28.023
They just wake up one morning
and go:

00:28.194 --> 00:31.254
"Oh, my God,
there's a tree inside the house.

00:31.698 --> 00:34.326
Just throw it anywhere."

00:40.907 --> 00:42.875
Ready to go, Lois?

00:43.109 --> 00:45.873
Boy, you sure like to say my name,
don't you?

00:46.046 --> 00:48.446
Excuse me, Lois.
Stand back, Lois.

00:48.615 --> 00:49.946
Jimmy's in trouble, Lois.

00:51.451 --> 00:53.817
Oh, Mr. Meyer,
this is my friend Jerry--

00:53.987 --> 00:58.219
-Jerry Seinfeld.
-Duncan Meyer.

00:58.391 --> 01:00.916
-You two know each other?
-Yeah.

01:01.094 --> 01:04.325
We went to high school together,
didn't we, Jerry?

01:04.497 --> 01:07.830
-Yeah, yeah.
-Gee, I hope you're not leaving now.

01:08.001 --> 01:10.265
We still have a lot of
work left to do.

01:10.437 --> 01:12.905
Would you be able to come
all the way downtown again...

01:13.073 --> 01:14.631
...in rush hour and pick me up?

01:15.108 --> 01:18.168
Why, I'd have to be Superman
to do that, Lois.

01:19.813 --> 01:22.008
No. No, this is all wrong.

01:22.182 --> 01:25.515
-Where's the chicken cashew?
-You no order chicken cashew.

01:26.252 --> 01:29.244
No, I didn't order any of this.
I'm not paying for this.

01:29.756 --> 01:30.984
Fine, Benes.

01:31.157 --> 01:32.647
We're putting you on our list.

01:33.026 --> 01:35.426
-What list?
-The do-not-deliver list.

01:36.429 --> 01:37.794
Merry Christmas to you.

01:40.700 --> 01:43.396
-Well, I guess we'll just go out.
-Yeah.

01:43.570 --> 01:45.629
What are you doing
with the <i>Daily Worker</i> ?

01:45.805 --> 01:47.796
I figure Ned must have left it here.

01:48.041 --> 01:51.442
Your boyfriend reads the <i>Daily
Worker</i> ? What is he, a Communist?

01:51.678 --> 01:54.169
He reads everything.
You know, Ned's very well-read.

01:54.447 --> 01:58.315
Maybe he's just very, well, Red.

02:01.321 --> 02:04.688
A Communist? Don't you think
he probably would have told me?

02:04.858 --> 02:08.122
Well, does he wear bland, drab,
olive-colored clothing?

02:08.661 --> 02:10.094
Yes.

02:10.263 --> 02:12.629
Yes, he does dress a little drab.

02:12.799 --> 02:14.664
He's a Communist.

02:15.802 --> 02:17.793
Hey, look at this.

02:18.004 --> 02:22.464
"Exciting, uninhibited woman
seeks forward-thinking comrade.

02:22.642 --> 02:25.133
Appearance not important."

02:25.311 --> 02:28.439
Appearance not important?
This is unbelievable.

02:28.615 --> 02:31.982
Finally, this an ideology
I can embrace.

02:32.619 --> 02:34.143
-Hey.
-Hey.

02:34.554 --> 02:36.215
-Where's Lois?
-She couldn't make it.

02:36.389 --> 02:38.914
I can't believe you're going out
with a woman named Lois.

02:39.092 --> 02:40.354
I know. Finally.

02:40.527 --> 02:42.620
But, George,
guess who her boss is?

02:42.795 --> 02:45.559
-Duncan Meyer.
-Duncan Meyer?

02:45.732 --> 02:47.165
-Who's he?
-Elaine...

02:47.333 --> 02:49.733
...only one person knows
what I'm about to tell you...

02:49.903 --> 02:51.461
...and that's George.

02:55.241 --> 02:59.007
In the ninth grade they had us all line
up in the schoolyard for this race...

02:59.179 --> 03:01.841
...to see who would represent
the school in this track meet.

03:02.115 --> 03:05.710
I was the last one on the end, George
was next to me and Mr. Bevilaqua--

03:05.885 --> 03:08.752
-What's that?
-Mr. Bevilaqua, the gym teacher.

03:08.922 --> 03:10.913
-Oh, of course.
-He was down at the other end.

03:11.090 --> 03:16.118
So he yells out, "Ready.
On your mark. Get set...."

03:16.296 --> 03:19.459
And I was so keyed up,
I just took off.

03:19.632 --> 03:22.100
By the time he said, "Go,"
I was ten yards ahead.

03:22.268 --> 03:23.496
-No.
-I looked up.

03:23.670 --> 03:25.035
I couldn't believe it.

03:25.205 --> 03:27.799
By the time the race was over,
I had won. I was shocked.

03:27.974 --> 03:30.340
-Nobody had noticed the head start.
-Really?

03:30.510 --> 03:32.239
Yes. And I had won by so much...

03:32.412 --> 03:35.575
...a myth began to grow
about my speed.

03:36.149 --> 03:38.276
Only Duncan suspected
something was amiss.

03:38.451 --> 03:40.578
He's hated me ever since.

03:40.753 --> 03:42.744
And now he's back.

03:43.489 --> 03:45.480
Well, what happened
when you raced him again?

03:45.658 --> 03:47.387
I never did.

03:48.328 --> 03:50.888
In four years of high school,
I would never race anyone...

03:51.064 --> 03:53.362
...not even to the end of a block
or to catch a bus.

03:53.666 --> 03:55.725
And so the legend grew.

03:55.902 --> 03:58.393
Everyone wanted me to race.
They begged me.

03:58.571 --> 04:02.166
The track coach called my parents,
pleading, telling them it was a sin...

04:02.342 --> 04:04.606
...for me to waste
my God-given talent.

04:04.777 --> 04:07.746
But I answered him in the same way
I answered everyone.

04:07.914 --> 04:10.246
I choose not to run.

04:12.752 --> 04:14.845
So now Duncan is back?

04:15.021 --> 04:16.988
He's back.

04:17.156 --> 04:19.750
As I knew he would be someday.

04:23.229 --> 04:25.697
Man, that's some tart cider.

04:29.669 --> 04:31.068
-Hi.
-Hi.

04:31.237 --> 04:34.263
-Sorry I missed the Chinese food.
-Oh, so am l.

04:34.440 --> 04:36.840
How's Duncan?

04:37.277 --> 04:39.074
He's okay.

04:39.445 --> 04:41.310
He say anything?

04:41.714 --> 04:42.942
About what?

04:43.716 --> 04:46.048
Oh, nothing in particular.

04:47.086 --> 04:49.611
-Why did you cheat in that race?
-I did not cheat.

04:49.789 --> 04:51.347
He said that you got a head start.

04:51.524 --> 04:54.357
Oh, he's just jealous
because he came in second.

04:54.527 --> 04:56.791
-Really?
-Yeah.

04:57.230 --> 04:59.494
So you were the fastest kid
in school.

05:00.400 --> 05:03.301
Faster than a speeding bullet, Lois.

05:05.772 --> 05:09.799
So how was work?
Another day, another dollar?

05:10.910 --> 05:13.174
-I guess.
-Yeah, well, nothing wrong with that.

05:13.346 --> 05:16.247
Gotta make those big bucks.

05:16.416 --> 05:19.112
Money, money, money.

05:19.819 --> 05:21.912
Are you a Communist?

05:24.290 --> 05:25.655
Yes, as a matter of fact, I am.

05:28.394 --> 05:29.986
A commie.

05:31.331 --> 05:32.764
Must be a bummer for you guys...

05:32.932 --> 05:35.730
...what with the fall of
the Soviet empire and everything.

05:36.035 --> 05:38.503
Well, yeah. Well,
we still got China, Cuba.

05:39.138 --> 05:42.130
Yeah, but come on.

05:43.509 --> 05:46.410
-I know. It's not the same.
-Well, you had a good run.

05:46.579 --> 05:50.015
I mean, what was it? Seventy-five,
80 years wreaking havoc...

05:50.183 --> 05:51.548
...making everybody nervous.

05:52.785 --> 05:54.412
Yeah, we had a good run.

05:54.587 --> 05:57.283
Well, so enjoy yourself.

06:00.760 --> 06:01.988
So you lied to her?

06:02.228 --> 06:05.823
I couldn't tell her the truth. I don't know
what's gonna happen between us.

06:06.032 --> 06:08.227
If we have a bad breakup,
she'll go to Duncan.

06:08.401 --> 06:12.565
I want him to go to his grave never
being certain that I got that head start.

06:13.272 --> 06:17.436
Well, I'm dating a Communist.

06:18.778 --> 06:21.804
-A Communist? That's something.
-Yeah, that's pretty cool, isn't it?

06:21.981 --> 06:23.710
Hey, I called one of those girls...

06:23.883 --> 06:26.613
...from the personal ads
in the <i>Daily Worker</i>.

06:26.886 --> 06:29.286
-The <i>Daily Worker</i> has personals?
-Yeah.

06:29.489 --> 06:33.050
And they say that appearance
is not important.

06:33.226 --> 06:35.217
Yours or hers?

06:37.830 --> 06:40.196
Merry Christmas, everyone.

06:40.366 --> 06:42.664
-Merry Christmas.
-Well, look at you.

06:42.835 --> 06:44.393
-You got the job.
-You're looking...

06:44.570 --> 06:47.767
...at the new Santa
at Coleman's Department Store.

06:47.940 --> 06:49.703
-All right. Way to go.
-Congratulations.

06:49.876 --> 06:52.106
Yeah. Feel that, isn't it great?

06:52.311 --> 06:54.575
Look, it's Mickey.

06:55.915 --> 06:58.042
Come on. Get your beard on.
We're gonna be late.

06:58.217 --> 07:01.482
On Prancer. On Dasher.
On Donna.

07:01.687 --> 07:03.518
It's not Donna. It's Donner.

07:03.689 --> 07:05.156
-It's Donna.
-Right. On Prancer.

07:05.324 --> 07:07.383
On Dancer. On Ethel. On Harriet.

07:11.297 --> 07:14.232
Hello. Oh, hi, Lois.

07:14.467 --> 07:17.368
He wants to get together?
What for?

07:17.570 --> 07:20.539
I don't know about that.
I'll have to think about it.

07:20.706 --> 07:23.937
-I'll let you know. Okay. Bye.
-What's up?

07:24.110 --> 07:26.101
Duncan wants to get together
with me and her.

07:26.279 --> 07:28.440
He's gonna try to get me
to admit I got a head start.

07:28.614 --> 07:30.206
I don't think she believes me.

07:30.383 --> 07:31.975
He wants to meet you?

07:32.151 --> 07:35.552
I'll tell you what. I'll show up.
He doesn't know we're friends.

07:35.721 --> 07:38.781
I'll pretend I haven't seen you
since school. I'll back up the story.

07:38.958 --> 07:40.755
-That's not bad.
-Not bad?

07:40.927 --> 07:42.622
It's gorgeous.

07:49.001 --> 07:52.164
Well, come on, little princess,
tell Santa what you want.

07:52.338 --> 07:55.671
-Don't be shy.
-She doesn't speak English.

07:55.875 --> 07:58.673
Oh, Santa speaks the language
of all children.

